ily Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gordon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Gordon in Berwickshire, named with Welsh <i>gor</i> ‘spacious’ + <i>din</i> ‘fort’.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Gourdon in Saône-et-Loire, so called from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Gordus</i> + the locative suffix <i>-o</i>, <i>-ōnis</i>.","English (of Norman origin): alternatively, said to be a nickname from a diminutive of Old French <i>gourd</i> ‘heavy, dull, sluggish’ (compare 8 below)."],"variants":[{"name":"Gordin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Eyal, Moisey, Yakov, Zalman, Erez, Faina, Haya, Mendel.  Russian Leonid, Aleksandr, Boris, Feiga, Genady.","Jewish (from Russia): variant of   Gordon   5.","French: variant of   Gourdin  . This surname is very rare in France."]},{"name":"Gordan","meanings":["German: variant of   Jordan  . The surname <i>Gordan</i> is very rare in Germany.","Irish (Wexford and Sligo): adopted as an Anglicized form of <b>Mag Mhuirneacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Muirneachán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>muirneach</i> ‘lovable’."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander de Gordon 3rd Laird of Gordon was born about 1160, in Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland, his father, Adam de Gordon 2nd Laird Gordon, was 26 and his mother, Mrs Adam De Gordon lll 2nd Laird Of Gordon, was 21. He had at least 2 sons with Unknown. He died in Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1160–":"umbes 1160–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1185–1270":"1185–1270","1200–1270":"1200–1270","1135–1170":"1135–1170","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1158":"1158","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1270":"1270","1160":"1160","about 1185":"umbes 1185","1170":"1170","Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Gordon, Berwickshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Berwick, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1160–":"noin 1160–Kuollut","1160–Male":"1160–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1185–1270":"1185–1270","1200–1270":"1200–1270","1135–1170":"1135–1170","1140–Female":"1140–Kuollut","about 1160":"noin 1160","1158":"1158","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","about 1200":"noin 1200","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1270":"1270","1160":"1160","about 1185":"noin 1185","1170":"1170","Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Gordon, Berwickshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Berwick, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1160–":"environ 1160–Décédé